5|$|During November, {{the real}} {{exchange}} rate (discounting inflation) of the Icelandic króna, as quoted by the Central Bank of Iceland, was roughly one-third {{lower than the}} average rate from 1980–2008, and 20% lower than the historical lows during the same period. The external rate as quoted by <b>the</b> <b>European</b> <b>Central</b> <b>Bank</b> was lower still. On the last trading day of the month, 28 November, the Central Bank of Iceland was quoting 182.5 krónur to the euro, while <b>the</b> <b>European</b> <b>Central</b> <b>Bank</b> was quoting 280 krónur to the euro.|$|E
